The paper discusses a logical framework for integrating different proof development tools and reducing the number of proof-irrelevant checks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the implementation of this framework in Coq, which is a proof assistant, indicating that it may also belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. The paper also mentions case studies on an emerging paradigm, which suggests that it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) or Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the use of this framework in CPUs and concurrency control, indicating that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category.
